s thought to be junk DNA, based on evidence that dates back fifty years. This conclusion is controversial. What’s in Your Genome? describes the arguments on both sides of the debate and attempts to explain the reasoning behind those different points of view. The book corrects a number of false narratives that have arisen in recent years and examines how they have affected the debate over junk DNA. In addition, Laurence A. Moran focuses on scientific misconceptions and misinformation and on how the junk DNA controversy has been incorrectly portrayed in both the scientific literature and the popular press. Tracing the earliest indications of junk DNA back to the 1960s, the book explains the success of nearly neutral theory and the importance of random genetic drift, which gave rise to the view that evolution produces sloppy genomes full of junk DNA. What’s in Your Genome? aims to offer the most accurate and current account of the human genome.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aGenomics. 0aHuman genome. 4aDISCOUNT-C. 7aSCIENCE / Life Sciences / Genetics & Genomics.2bisacsh  aENCODE.  aRNA.  aalternative splicing.  acentromeres.  afunction wars.  agenes.  agenetic drift.  ajunk DNA.  amutation.  anoncoding DNA.  aorigins of replication.  apopular science.  apopulation genetics.  asloppy genome.  atransposons.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311127195808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311079736740uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978148753856940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781487538569423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781487538569/original  a978-3-11-079736-7  University of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  a978-3-11-127